{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d67da8d4-202a-43d8-be8b-f3c9dec2f6d0","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports — no `createdump` needed:\n\n1. **Crash reports (.ips files)** are saved to:\n   - `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (user apps)\n   - `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (system-wide)\n\n2. Look for a file matching your process name, e.g.:\n   ```\n   ls ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/MyApp*.ips\n   ```\n\n3. You can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them.\n\n4. For a **core dump**, enable them with:\n   ```\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n> **Note:** macOS SIP may prevent core dumps for certain processes. The `.ips` crash report is usually the most reliable artifact on macOS.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"85cd1bcb-427f-434e-9bd4-a9482fee237b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a diagnostics question, not a code task. Let me answer directly from my knowledge.","outputTokens":292,"requestId":"A0C9:16715D:980410:BA2986:6A01366D"},"id":"8b35d9f5-cf03-4f1c-ad72-55eb92626c09","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:52:55.765Z","parentId":"50e2d99d-d437-4c32-ba14-96061b51f733"}
